    slug: "development-of-science-technology-in-islamic-history",
    description: `Development of Science & Technology in Islamic History is a scholarly book that traces the remarkable contributions of Muslim civilization to the fields of science, technology, medicine, mathematics, astronomy, chemistry, physics, engineering, and architecture during the Islamic Golden Age and beyond. The book presents a comprehensive historical narrative that challenges the common misconception that the Islamic world was merely a passive transmitter of ancient Greek and Persian knowledge to medieval Europe. Instead, it demonstrates through detailed evidence and specific examples how Muslim scientists, inventors, physicians, and engineers made original discoveries, developed innovative technologies, and established scientific institutions that advanced human knowledge for centuries.

The book is organized chronologically and thematically, beginning with the early Islamic period and the Quranic and prophetic injunctions that encouraged the pursuit of knowledge. It examines how the translation movement in Baghdad, centered around the Bayt al-Hikmah (House of Wisdom), served as a catalyst for scientific inquiry by making classical texts available in Arabic, which then became the lingua franca of the scientific world. The narrative then progresses through the major periods of Islamic scientific achievement, documenting the work of figures such as Al-Khwarizmi, who developed algebra and introduced the numeral system that bears the misnomer "Arabic numerals"; Ibn al-Haytham, the father of optics and the scientific method; Al-Biruni, who made groundbreaking contributions to geology, astronomy, and comparative religion; Ibn Sina (Avicenna), whose Canon of Medicine remained the standard medical textbook in European universities for over five hundred years; and Jabir ibn Hayyan, considered the father of chemistry. The book also covers advances in agriculture and irrigation technology, the development of sophisticated astronomical instruments such as the astrolabe, innovations in shipbuilding and navigation, the construction of monumental architectural works that demonstrated advanced engineering principles, and the establishment of the world's first universities and hospitals.

Written primarily in Arabic with the academic rigor expected of serious historical scholarship, this book is intended for students and scholars of Islamic history, the history of science, and anyone interested in understanding the full scope of Muslim contributions to human civilization. It serves as an important corrective to Eurocentric narratives that marginalize or ignore the Islamic world's role in the development of modern science. The detailed references, chronological tables, and biographical sketches of key scientists make this book a valuable reference work that can be consulted for specific information or read cover to cover for a comprehensive understanding of the subject. It is particularly useful for educators who want to present a balanced and accurate account of the history of science to their students, and for Muslim readers who want to appreciate the rich intellectual heritage of their civilization.`,
    metaDescription: "Development of Science & Technology in Islamic History documents Muslim contributions to science and medicine. A comprehensive scholarly reference."
