    slug: "dictionary-of-islamic-names",
    description: `Dictionary of Islamic Names is a comprehensive English-language reference book that provides an extensive collection of Muslim names along with their meanings, origins, linguistic roots, and cultural significance within the Islamic tradition. Naming a child is one of the most important decisions Muslim parents make, as Islamic teachings emphasize that a person's name carries weight in this world and influences their identity throughout their life. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) encouraged Muslims to choose good names and to avoid names with negative or inappropriate connotations, making this dictionary an essential tool for families seeking guidance on this important matter.

The book organizes its entries alphabetically for easy reference, with each name entry typically including the name in its original Arabic script where applicable, the transliterated spelling, the linguistic root from which the name is derived, the literal meaning of the name, and any significant historical or religious associations. Names drawn from the Quran are clearly marked, allowing parents who wish to choose a Quranic name to identify suitable options quickly. The book includes names of the prophets mentioned in the Quran, the companions of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), the righteous predecessors (Salaf al-Salih), and other historically significant Muslim figures. It also covers the names of Allah (Asma ul-Husna) that are permissible for human use, with clear guidance on which divine names are appropriate for people and which should be reserved exclusively for Allah.

Beyond its function as a simple name-finding tool, this dictionary provides contextual information that helps parents understand the deeper significance of the names they are considering. The linguistic analysis of each name connects it to broader Quranic themes and Islamic values, helping parents choose names that reflect qualities they hope their children will embody. The book also includes a section on the Islamic rulings and recommendations regarding naming, drawn from authentic hadith sources and the opinions of classical scholars. It addresses common questions such as whether it is permissible to use non-Arabic Muslim names, the ruling on names that have associations with shirk or polytheism, the etiquette of changing one's name upon embracing Islam, and the recommendation to name children after prophets and righteous individuals. This makes the book useful not only for expectant parents but also for new Muslims who are choosing their own Islamic names, Islamic school teachers who assist students with name-related questions, and anyone interested in the rich onomastic tradition of Islam.`,
    metaDescription: "Dictionary of Islamic Names offers an extensive collection of Muslim names with meanings and Islamic significance. Essential guide for parents."
