    slug: "dosti-or-dushmani",
    description: `Dosti or Dushmani (Friendship and Enmity) is an Urdu-language Islamic book that addresses the Islamic framework governing social relationships, specifically focusing on the concepts of friendship (dosti) and enmity (dushmani) as understood through the lens of Islamic teachings drawn from the Quran and the authentic hadith of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him). The book examines one of the most consequential aspects of human social life — the choices we make about whom to befriend, whom to keep at a distance, and how to navigate relationships with those who oppose us or hold different beliefs. In Islam, these are not merely social matters but moral and spiritual decisions that have profound implications for a person's faith, character, and ultimate destiny.

The book begins by establishing the Quranic and prophetic foundation for understanding Islamic social bonds. It presents the Quranic injunctions regarding friendship and companionship, including the verses that warn against taking disbelievers as close allies and protectors (awliya) at the expense of the believers, while also emphasizing the importance of treating all people with justice and kindness regardless of their faith. The book carefully distinguishes between different levels of social interaction — the obligation of basic kindness and fair treatment toward all people, the permissibility of business and professional relationships with non-Muslims, and the special bond of religious friendship and brotherhood that is reserved for fellow believers. This nuanced treatment helps readers understand that Islamic teachings on this topic are balanced and practical rather than encouraging isolation or hostility.

The section on friendship (dosti) elaborates on the qualities that Islam encourages in choosing friends, drawing from the Prophet's guidance that a person is on the religion of their close companion. The book identifies the characteristics of a righteous friend — one who encourages good deeds, discourages wrongdoing, reminds one of Allah, is truthful and trustworthy, and supports during difficult times. It also warns against the dangers of keeping bad company, citing the hadith that compares good and bad companions to a musk seller and a blacksmith. The section on enmity (dushmani) addresses the Islamic etiquette of dealing with opponents and enemies, emphasizing the Quranic teaching that good and evil are not equal and that repelling evil with good is the highest moral conduct. The book discusses the permissibility and conditions of enmity for the sake of Allah, the obligation to maintain justice even toward those one dislikes, the prohibition of unjust treatment and transgression, and the virtues of forgiveness and reconciliation. Written in clear Urdu, this book is suitable for general readers, students of Islamic studies, and anyone seeking to align their social relationships with Islamic principles.`,
    metaDescription: "Dosti or Dushmani explores the Islamic framework of friendship and enmity. Quranic guidance on choosing companions and handling social relationships."
