    slug: "dua-aur-dawa-kai-masnoon-adaab-jadeed",
    description: `Dua Aur Dawa Kai Masnoon Adaab (Jadeed) by Abdul Khaliq Muhammad Sadiq is an updated and expanded Urdu-language book that provides a comprehensive guide to the prophetic etiquettes and methods related to supplication (dua) and seeking medical treatment (dawa). The word "Masnoon" in the title indicates that the book focuses specifically on practices that are established through the Sunnah of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), ensuring that readers receive guidance grounded in authentic Islamic sources rather than cultural customs or innovations. The "Jadeed" (new/updated) designation indicates that this edition incorporates additional content, revised explanations, and contemporary guidance that addresses modern situations and questions that were not covered in earlier editions.

The dua section of the book covers the complete spectrum of Islamic supplication etiquette as taught by the Prophet. It details the proper times for making dua, including during prostration, the last third of the night, between the adhan and iqamah, while fasting, on Fridays, and during rainfall. The book explains the postures and physical gestures recommended during dua, such as raising the hands, facing the qiblah, and the specific manner in which the hands should be raised according to different hadith narrations. It covers the recommended opening praises and phrases with which a person should begin their supplication, the importance of persistence in dua, the etiquettes of making dua for others, the permissibility and conditions of making dua in a group setting, and the common mistakes and misunderstandings that people have regarding dua. The book includes a substantial collection of authentic duas from the Quran and hadith for various life situations, organized by category for easy reference.

The dawa (medicine/treatment) section addresses the Islamic perspective on seeking medical treatment, drawing on the hadith that establishes a fundamental principle of Islamic theology: that Allah has not sent down any disease without also sending down its cure. The book covers the prophetic recommendations regarding specific remedies, including the use of honey, black seed (kalonji), cupping (hijamah), and various foods mentioned in the hadith as having medicinal properties. It also provides guidance on the Islamic ruling regarding visiting doctors, taking prescribed medication, the permissibility of using both traditional and modern medical treatments, and the proper balance between reliance upon Allah (tawakkul) and taking practical steps to seek healing. The author addresses contemporary medical questions that Muslims commonly face, including vaccinations, surgical procedures, mental health treatment, and the use of medicines that contain impermissible ingredients under conditions of necessity. This updated edition makes the book a practical and relevant resource for Urdu-speaking Muslims seeking to align their approach to supplication and healthcare with authentic Islamic teachings.`,
