    slug: "dua-ki-qabuliat-k-ahkaam-o-adaab",
    description: `Dua ki Qabuliat k Ahkaam o Adaab (The Rulings and Etiquettes of Dua Acceptance) by Fazeela Shaykh Abdullah Al-Khizri is an Urdu-language Islamic book that provides a focused and detailed examination of the conditions, impediments, etiquettes, and signs related to the acceptance of supplication. While many Islamic books compile duas for various occasions, this book takes a different approach by analyzing the factors that determine whether a dua is accepted, partially accepted, or not accepted, based on the Quranic guidance and authentic prophetic traditions. The author systematically presents the ahkaam (rulings) and adaab (etiquettes) that surround the practice of dua, offering readers a thorough understanding of how to make dua in a manner that is most likely to be accepted by Allah.

The book begins with the Quranic foundation for dua, citing verses such as Allah's statement that He is close to His servants when they call upon Him, and the verse commanding believers to call upon Allah with humility and in private. It then establishes the core principle that dua is an act of worship (ibadah) in itself, not merely a tool for requesting things, which means that the rules governing worship — sincerity, proper intention, adherence to the prophetic method — apply to dua as well. The author identifies and explains the conditions for dua acceptance as described in the hadith, including the requirement that the dua be made solely to Allah without associating any partners, that the person making dua must be earning lawful income from halal sources, that the dua must not involve cutting off family ties, and that the person must not be hasty or impatient in expecting a response.

The book provides a detailed discussion of the factors that can prevent dua from being accepted, drawing from the well-known hadith in which the Prophet listed specific actions that cause dua to be rejected. These include consuming haram (unlawful) income, being heedless and negligent in one's worship, making dua for something sinful or harmful, being impatient and saying "I made dua but was not answered," and having doubt about Allah's ability to respond. For each impediment, the author provides the relevant hadith evidence and practical advice on how to address and remove that barrier. The section on etiquettes covers the recommended times, places, and situations in which dua is most likely to be accepted, the physical postures and verbal formulas recommended by the Prophet, the importance of persistence and consistency in making dua, and the virtues of making dua for others before making dua for oneself. The author also discusses how Allah responds to dua in three ways — granting what was asked, warding off an equivalent harm, or storing the reward for the Hereafter — helping readers understand that a delayed or seemingly unanswered dua does not mean it was rejected. This book is particularly valuable for Urdu-speaking Muslims who want to deepen their understanding of the spiritual mechanics of supplication and ensure that their duas are made in accordance with the prophetic methodology.`,
    metaDescription: "Dua ki Qabuliat k Ahkaam o Adaab by Fazeela Shaykh Al-Khizri explains conditions for accepted supplications. Urdu guide to dua etiquettes and impediments."
